{{Infobox prepared food | name = Basler Läckerli | image = Basler Läckerli 01.jpeg | image_size = 250px | caption = | alternate_name = Leckerli, läggerli | country = [[Switzerland]] | region = [[Basel]] | creator = | course = | type = [[Biscuit]] | served = | main_ingredient = [[Honey]], [[hazelnut]]s, [[almond]]s, [[candied peel]], [[Kirsch]] | variations = | calories = | other = }}
The '''Basler Läckerli''' (also '''Leckerli''' or '''Läggerli''', ''lecker'' meaning "delicious" in [[German language|German]] and ''-li'' being a [[Diminutive#German|diminutive]] suffix) is a traditional hard [[spice]] [[biscuit]] originating from [[Basel]], [[Switzerland]]. It is made of [[honey]], [[hazelnuts]], [[almond]]s, [[candied peel]], and [[Kirsch]]. The flat baked dough is, when still hot, cut into rectangular pieces. It is then topped with a sugar glaze.
Basler Läckerli were originally created by local spice merchants over 700 years ago and is available year-round.<ref>{{cite web |author=Annika Mengisen |title=Holiday Shopping, Swiss Style |url=http://www.thestreet.com/funds/toponepercent/10325941.html |work=The Street |date=8 December 2006 |accessdate=2009-02-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090413202712/http://www.thestreet.com/funds/toponepercent/10325941.html |archivedate=2009-04-13 |df= }}</ref>
