{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}} {{Infobox newspaper | name = Democracia | logo = | image = | caption = | type = Weekly | format = | owners = | founder = | publisher = | editor = | chiefeditor = | assoceditor = | maneditor = | newseditor = | managingeditordesign = | campuseditor = | campuschief = | opeditor = | sportseditor = | photoeditor = | seniorstaff = | staff = | foundation = | political = Republican | language = [[Spanish language]] | ceased publication = | relaunched = | headquarters = [[Petit Socco]], [[Tangier]] | circulation = | sister newspapers = | ISSN = | oclc = | website = }} '''''Democracia''''' (''English: Democracy'') was a [[Spanish language]] Republican weekly newspaper published from [[Tangier]], [[Morocco]].<ref name="p2">''[https://books.google.com/books?id=IlnQAAAAMAAJ Nomenclature des journaux & revues en langue française du monde entier]''. Paris, Les bureaux de l'Argus, 1937. p. 466</ref><ref name="g2">Stuart, Graham H. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=VGqmAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA107 The International City of Tangier]''. Stanford, Calif: Stanford University Press, 1955. p. 107</ref> The office of ''Democracia'' was located at [[Petit Socco]].<ref name="g2"/>
On 27 December 1936 the offices of ''Democracia'' was attacked by a large group of Italian sailors, who vandalised the building and threatened to kill the editor. Returning from the attack, they sang the fascist hymn ''Giovinezza''.<ref name="h2">"Hispanicus". Foreign Intervention in Spain. London: United Editorial Ltd, 1938. pp. 289-290</ref> The attack was interpreted at the time as indicative of the Italian support for [[Francisco Franco]]'s revolt against the government in [[Madrid]].<ref name="g2"/><ref name="h2"/>
